Introduction¶

This analysis will explore relationships/trends between the 2016 Census and FBI Gun Data.

  • Questions to be explored:
    • Which factors are most correlated with gun registration in 2016?
    • Which states Per Capita had the most guns registered in 2016?
    • Which state has seen the most growth in gun registration in the last decade?

For this analysis I will be using pandas_bokeh and bokeh plotting for my visualizations for two reasons:

  • To explore options outside the normal scope of Udacity projects
  • Make the graph's interactive for the end user

The cell below is used to install bokeh in the Jupyter Notebook

Data Wrangling¶

General Properties¶

Below I loaded the data files from a csv and excel format into their respective dataframes and utilize methods to determine what the data looks like in its raw form.

Methods Used:¶

  • df.head(): to determine if the csv/excel files pulled in correctly and did not have another delimiter
  • df.shape(): to explore the number of columns and rows in the data
  • df.info(): to explore data types and missing values
  • df.describe(): To explore summary stats
  • df.isnull: to explore null values and determine how I want to fill or drop them

Census Data Cleaning¶

Now that I see the data has successfully loaded, there are steps I want to take to clean the census data which include:

  • Handling Nulls
  • Transposing the data
  • Dropping Columns
  • Changing the Data Types

New Data Types¶

With the now transposed Census Data, I can see that all my data values are of the numeric type, but my data types are strings. In this next section I will transform the data from Strings to floats and ints

Using df_census.astype(float) method to convert strings to floats/ints will give me an error because of the "," "%" "$" and '"'symbols. I will replace these values with their counterparts without the symbols.

In [16]:
for i in df_census:
    df_census[i]= df_census[i].apply(lambda x: x.replace(",",""))
    df_census[i]= df_census[i].apply(lambda x: x.replace("%",""))
    df_census[i]= df_census[i].apply(lambda x: x.replace("$", ""))
    df_census[i]= df_census[i].apply(lambda x: x.replace('"',""))

Research Question 3¶

Which state Per Capita purchased the most guns in 2016¶

First lest's describe Per Capita according to this link from Indeed Per Capita is described as the following:

"Calculating per capita entails taking into account a measurement or number amount by which you will then divide by the total population of the group wishing to be analyzed. The following formula can be used to determine the per capita:"
Per capita = measurement/number of people in a population

With this in mind I would need to divide gun total per state by total population in the year 2016

Here I create a new dataframe with the 2016 population grouped by State

Conclusions¶

Results¶

From our three questions and analysis we can conclude the following:

  • These Seven Features are most associated with gun registration:

    • Population estimates, July 1, 2016, (V2016)
    • Housing units, July 1, 2016, (V2016)
    • Households, 2011-2015
    • Total manufacturers shipments, 2012 (1,000 USD)
    • Total retail sales, 2012 (1,000 USD)
    • Total employment, 2015,
    • Nonminority-owned firms, 2012

  • In 2016 based off the population estimates Kentucky had the highest gun registrations per capita

  • From 2007 to 2017 Maryland had the highest growth in gun registrations.

What can we do with this information?

  • If you're in the gun business, this could help you target your gun campaign for the growing markets
  • If you're not a fan of guns it can show you what states to be weary to move to if you were to relocate.

There are plenty of other questions that can be answered from this dataset this was just the tip of the iceberg. As I begin to learn more about statistical analysis my conclusions will be more robust.

Limitations¶

  • This data was based from 2016 estimates so the actual results from 2016 could change the analysis
  • Certain columns units were still left as percentages because they were not a percentage of the 2016 population. If this data was available, it could effect our correlation matrix
  • When cleaning the Gun data set 5830(46%) rows were dropped in order to only keep one decade of data. If we were looking at the full data set our results may vary
  • The statistical analysis used in this dataset was descriptive and not inferential. Meaning we are only describing relationships and not making any predictions
